cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this software, please cite it as below."
title: "edaphos: Disruptive Algorithms for Digital Soil Mapping"
abstract: >-
  edaphos is a research-oriented R package implementing frontier
  algorithms for Digital Soil Mapping (DSM) beyond the regression-tree
  state of the art. It is organised across six research pillars,
  each confronting a specific methodological gap of the literature:
  (1) Causal AI with backdoor-adjusted effect estimation on
  pedogenetic Directed Acyclic Graphs, demonstrated on 1095 real
  WoSIS Cerrado profiles (v1.4.0); (2) Physics-Informed Machine
  Learning of the soil depth profile via a parametric pedogenetic
  ODE and a differentiable Neural ODE, including a covariate-
  conditioned hierarchical extension across pedons; (3) 4D
  Pedometry with a multi-layer stacked Convolutional LSTM,
  sequence-to-sequence training, multi-step rollout forecasting, an
  optional physics-informed mass-balance loss and a stochastic
  Ensemble Kalman Filter with optional Gaspari-Cohn localization
  for sequential assimilation of new in-situ observations on a
  real MODIS + NASA POWER Cerrado cube (v1.5.0); (4) Foundation
  Models via SimCLR / MoCo-v2 contrastive pre-training on
  unlabelled raster covariate patches; (5) Autonomous Active
  Learning with a hybrid uncertainty and feature-space-diversity
  batch policy, logistical cost-aware extension, and Physics-
  Informed rejection gates; (6) Quantum ML with a pure-R
  state-vector simulator of the ZZFeatureMap encoding, a quantum
  kernel Gram matrix and a closed-form Kernel Ridge Regression
  wrapper, optionally dispatched to IBM Quantum Runtime via
  qiskit. A unified uncertainty API based on a common
  `edaphos_posterior` S3 class plus a CRPS / PICP / MPIW
  calibration diagnostic exposes every pillar through the same
  three-line recipe (v1.6.0). v1.7.0 introduces a capstone
  cross-pillar vignette that integrates all six pillars in a
  single Cerrado sampling-campaign narrative, causally grounded
  in the generative DSM framework of Zhang and Wadoux (2026).
  v1.7.1 adds a native-query calibration bundle, evaluating
  each pillar in its natural domain (scalar effect, depth
  profile, future map, spatial map, held-out regression) so the
  calibration table is scientifically honest rather than a
  domain-mismatched artifact. v1.7.2 ships a causal-discovery
  benchmark that compares expert, LLM-augmented, and three
  data-driven (bnlearn hc / tabu / pc-stable) DAGs on the same
  1 095 WoSIS Cerrado profiles, with Structural Hamming
  Distance matrix, consensus edges, and sensitivity of the
  backdoor adjustment set for MAP -> SOC. v1.8.0 adds a
  multi-backend LLM extraction benchmark (Gemma 4 + GPT-4o-mini
  + Claude Sonnet-4.5) against a 30-abstract gold-standard with
  72 annotated Cerrado pedogenesis claims, producing
  per-backend precision / recall / F1, pairwise Cohen's kappa,
  cost / 1k-claims estimates, and latency distributions -- the
  infrastructure for scaling Pillar 1 to a 10 000-abstract
  literature corpus.  v1.8.1 adds a two-phase annotation tooling
  (llm_preannotate + llm_annotation_launch) with a Shiny review
  UI, controlled vocabulary, resume-safe JSONL caching, and
  keyboard shortcuts, so a domain expert can scale a
  gold-standard from 72 to 300+ claims in a few hours via
  accept/edit/reject over LLM drafts.  v1.8.2 extends the
  tool with an OpenAlex corpus fetcher
  (data-raw/cerrado_corpus_v2_fetch.R) producing up to 150
  deduplicated real abstracts, a DAG-preview tab that renders
  the aggregated accepted-claim graph live, a dark-mode theme
  toggle, and an llm_annotation_to_zenodo() packager that
  bundles the reviewed KG + RDF 1.1 Turtle serialisation +
  DataCite-compatible metadata into a zip ready for upload
  to zenodo.org/deposit/new.
